{"id": "c9_b_00391", "url": "https://www.worcesternews.co.uk/news/23858136.gran-takes-sahara-trek-acorns-childrens-hospice/", "time": "2023-10-17", "title": "Epic Sahara trek for Acorns Children’s Hospice in memory of grandson", "text": "A grandmother is taking on an epic trek across the hottest and most famous desert in the world in memory of her brave grandson.\nVicki Bace says she is looking forward to the adventure of a lifetime when she walks across the Sahara to remember little Arthur Spackman, who was cared for by Acorns for the Three Counties in Worcester.\nShe will be hiking 50km across hot sands along with a team of other intrepid explorers all raising money to help the charity continue its essential care for children with life limiting or life threatening conditions.\n“I absolutely hate spiders, it’s those legs,” Vicki said. “The most important thing on this trip is to make sure no camel spiders come and chase me. Apparently, they run towards you for the shade.”\nShe added: “But Arthur will be in my thoughts the whole time. He defied the odds, and if he could do that, then I can do this.”\nArthur was given just weeks to live after being born with a rare genetic disorder, but bravely fought the condition and was two years old when he sadly died in 2019.\nVicki said: “We are forever grateful to Acorns. The charity affected our lives with the support they gave. We were scared and emotional, but knowing we were well supported, knowing Arthur was looked after, I knew we were safe as well.\n“Without fundraising, Acorns and the amazing work they do would not exist. Until you realise, you do not understand the importance of it. So, I’m making other people aware and I’m doing to make sure Acorns is here for families like mine long into the future.”\nThe whole family, along with Arthur’s mum and dad Charlene and Ashley, has since undertaken various fundraising activities for the charity, organised by Arthur’s uncle Chris Anderson, including charity walks and cycling challenges.\nNow Vicki will join the #TeamAcorns Sahara Trek 2023 which got underway on October 14. She will also be accompanied by Chris and together they have so far raised more than £6,500 on their JustGiving page.\nThe trek will last eight days and take the team of 27 amazing Acorns supporters to Marrakech to follow ancient caravan routes across the desert and the Atlas Mountains.\nVicki said: “I wanted to do something that was out of my comfort zone. I turned 50 this year. I’m doing it in my sister’s memory too.\nShe added: “We are going to be sore and sleep deprived. Chris is also trying to get me to sleep under the stars. But I’m not going out there with those bugs. You don’t know what will crawl onto you!”\nAcorns Children’s Hospice provides specialist palliative care for children and young people with life limiting and life threatening conditions and support for their families.\nIn the past year, the charity has cared for more than 700 children across the Black Country and wider West Midlands, and almost 1,000 families, including those who are bereaved.\nAcorns needs around £27,000 each day to provide its children’s hospice care, with two thirds of that amount coming from generous donations and fundraising by the local community.\nVisit Vicki and Chris' fundraising at: https://www.justgiving.com/fundraising/chris-anderson58\nFind out how you can help #TeamAcorns by visiting their JustGiving page at: https://www.justgiving.com/campaign/AcornsSaharaTrek2023"}
