gender fluid perfumes?\nAccording to French perfumer Francis Kurkdijian, founder of the eponymous perfume house, everything. Gender neutral scents have been around for a long time, and are designed to be worn and loved by people identifying as any gender due to their blend of notes that have traditionally been divided between perfumes for men and women respectively.\n“But fluidity doesn’t mean genderless. We have to be very specific in our vocabulary,” explains Kurkdjian. “Gender fluidity means one to another, to be able to transition in a fluid manner. This is very very different [to a unisex fragrance].”\nWhat do unisex fragrances smell like?\nUnisex fragrances, by design, encompass a wide spectrum of scents that defy traditional gender categorisations. They are characterised by their versatility and often feature a balanced blend of notes that appeal to a broad audience. Ranging from fresh and citrusy to woody and musky, they often strike a harmonious balance between floral, spicy, and herbal elements.\nUnisex fragrances tend to be less overtly masculine or feminine, making them suitable for anyone who appreciates a scent that transcends conventional boundaries. Ultimately, the beauty of unisex fragrances lies in their ability to adapt to individual preferences and evoke a sense of timeless elegance that appeals to a diverse range of individuals.\nWhere do I buy unisex perfumes?\nUnisex perfumes are becoming more and more common. According to a new products survey done by Mintel, gender-neutral fragrance releases made up 17 per cent of the market in 2010, and by 2018 that figure had ballooned to 51 per cent.\nYou might have grown up spritzing perfumes on at department stores, but now, many of us are shopping online for our scents. Adore Beauty stocks a whole range, including Aesop, Amouage and Who Is Elijah, while make-up stores like Sephora and Mecca have dedicated fragrance sections. For international fragrances that can be hard to source in stores across Australia, major international online retailers like Sense and Selfridges can also be a great option.\nOriginally published as Fluid form: 18 unisex fragrances for universal appeal"}
{"id": "c9_b_00439", "url": "https://www.dailytelegraph.com.au/lifestyle/best-unisex-perfumes/news-story/c3034b9034987f3a8feb7351c84b2c29?nk=a490fd7ce6c72c0ceaa0b9dae38ac7ac-1700378188", "time": "2024-06-26", "title": "Fluid form: 18 unisex fragrances for universal appeal", "text": "Fluid form: 18 unisex fragrances for universal appeal\nFrom Byredo to Le Labo to Who Is Elijah, here are our picks of the best unisex perfumes that don’t conform.\nFrom Byredo to Le Labo to Who Is Elijah, here are our picks of the best unisex perfumes that don’t conform.\nVogue Australia may receive advertising or affiliate commission if you buy through our links. Read more here.\nHers, mine, yours, theirs. Fragrance has long moved beyond the realm of binary gender to embrace a fluid way of being: gone are the strict delineations between florals and musk for women and spice and woodiness for men. We’re complex, our tastes are varied, and our fragrances will be too across all top, middle and base notes.\nStrangely enough, the gender divide in the fragrance world is a relatively recent invention. In the Middle Ages, fragrances were drawn from natural sources—flowers, wood—to mask natural odours in men and women, until marketing in the late 20th century began to emphasise the distinctions between genders. But in the mid-1990s, Calvin Klein's CK One, a now-iconic unisex scent, entered the fragrance cosmos: it heralded a bold new era, where a clean, striking scent profile could be worn by anyone and signature scents had to be neither inherently masculine or feminine.\nNow, Australian brands are also joining the international game. Who Is Elijah, the cult favourite you’re seeing all over Instagram packages up sexy, enigmatic scents in sparse, minimal bottles for an all-round sensory experience. Mihan Aromatics, designed by a Fitzroy couple, also has a four-product range of fragrances designed to mimic the smells and surrounds of the pair’s home, and of their favourite local haunts.\nBelow, our picks of the best unisex and gender-neutral fragrances to shop right now.\nVogue’s top picks\n- Best luxury unisex fragrance: Byredo Velvet Haze eau de parfum\n- Best affordable unisex fragrance: Calvin Klein CK One eau de toilette\n- Best Australian unisex fragrance: Who Is Elijah His | Her\n- Best floral unisex fragrance: Full Ylang Ylang eau de parfum\n- Best spice unisex fragrance: Aesop Hwyl eau de parfum\nThe best unisex, gender-neutral fragrances of 2024\nWho Is Elijah\nHis | Her\nWith sweet, spicy top notes sitting on a bed of verdant freshness, Australian label Who Is Elijah makes the ultimate go-between scent—and, what's more, the female-owned and run brand takes its clean credentials seriously.\nSize: 100ml | Key notes: Bergamot, violet leaf, cardamom, fir needle, sandalwood, cashmere musk | Shipping: Free delivery\nCustomer experience: “I love the scent so much I bought another bottle… It smells sophisticated and I get heaps of compliments. It wears long/strong and I still get hints of it at the end of the day,” one customer writes. Read more reviews here.\nJo Malone London\nLondon Wood Sage & Sea Salt cologne\nFrom fragrance powerhouse Jo Malone London, this earthy sage and wood forward cologne mixed with fresh sea salt evokes a windswept coastal shore, breaking waves and rugged cliffs, making it a perfect neutral scent for the spring and summer months.\nSize: 50ml | Key notes: Ambrette seeds, sea salt, sage | Shipping: Free delivery\nCustomer experience: “This is summer in a bottle,” writes one reviewer. Read more reviews here.\nAmouage\nMeander eau de parfum\nReleased in 2020, Amouage’s jade bottle with a stone-studded neck hides a complex, layered fragrance. It pays homage to the monsoon season in the plateaus of Oman, the brand’s home country, with spicy, woody notes that stay green and springy.\nSize: 100ml | Key notes: Olibanum oil, carrot heart, pink pepper, black pepper oil, orris, rose, cypriol Heart, vetiver oil | Shipping: Free delivery\nCustomer experience: “This fragrance is beautiful and unique. It’s quite gentle and I find that the opening fades into the mid very quickly on my skin. The opening to me feels almost as if you’re eating a lavender and green tea flavoured desert. I also get a slight hint of pepper shortly after spraying but it isn’t overbearing at all. This fragrance is completely unisex to me but I find this to be a particularly gentlemanly fragrance,” one reviewer writes. Read more reviews here.\nMihan Aromatics\nMikado Bark parfum\nMelbourne-based perfumers Mihan Aromatics have created a scant, clean line of fragrances utilising native ingredients with reserve and grace. This one brings back the scent of the Fitzroy Gardens on long summer evenings.\nSize: 100ml | Key notes: Green pepper, rosemary, basil, dry cinnamon, oud, sandalwood, wet cedar | Shipping: Free delivery\nCustomer experience: “This scent is wonderful! Not too sweet, not too woody, but a nice mix of the two and a bit earthy,” one reviewer writes. Read more reviews here.\nCalvin Klein\nCK One eau de toilette\nNo gender-neutral fragrance list would be complete without the scent that hung in the air throughout the late 1990s. This iconic option by Calvin Klein is clean, youthful and citrus-laden.\nSize: 100ml | Key notes: Green tea, bergamot, cardamon, violet, rose, nutmeg, amber, musk | Shipping: Free delivery over $99\nCustomer experience: “This spray is so beautiful! It's not too overpowering but it has a nice, fresh and clean scent. Perfect for both me and my partner to use,” writes one reviewer. Read more reviews here.\nAesop\nHwyl eau de parfum\nKnown for its earthy, unorthodox formulations, Aesop brings you a smoky, spicy medley of a fragrance in Hwyl—with warm heart notes flecked with vetiver, thyme and moss, this fragrances hints at a unisex floral scent without the sweetness.\nSize: 50ml | Key notes: Thyme, elemi, nutmeg, cypress, geranium, suede, vetiver, cedarwood, patchouli | Shipping: Free delivery\nCustomer experience: “This perfume has been my signature scent for a year now. It's rich and earthy, I love it,” writes one reviewer. Read more reviews here.\nBDK Parfums\nVelvet Tonka eau de parfum\nA fragrance that is sometimes bitter and sometimes sweet as it evolves throughout the wear, inspired by the smells of Morocco and the Atlas Mountains, and a symbol of unisex sensuality with a slight feminine lean, Velvet Tonka by BDK Parfums is a unique, powdery and vintage scent.\nSize: 100ml | Key notes: Orange blossom, almond, rose absolute, tobacco absolute, vanilla absolute, amyris wood essence, amber woods | Shipping: Free delivery\nCustomer experience: “This beautiful perfume is the most gorgeous perfume. It smells utterly sweet and divine. I cannot get enough of it. I get so many compliments when I wear it,” writes one reviewer. Read more reviews here.\nClarins\nEau Dynamisante treatment fragrance\nLeading with sweet and bitter orange, combined with lavandin and eucalyptus and followed by patchouli, Eau Dynamisante by Clarins boasts a fresh, light aroma as well as a stimulating and energising effect on the skin—turning this natural, citrus forward fragrance into a multi-use product.\nSize: 100ml | Key notes: Sweet and bitter orange, mandarin, petitgrain, lavandin, eucalyptus, tarragon, nutmeg, patchouli | Shipping: Free delivery\nCustomer experience: “This is the scent of white linen and a cool breeze,” reads one review. Read more reviews here.\nMalin + Goetz\nDark Rum eau de parfum\nLiquor me up. This dark, sultry fragrance features top notes of bergamot and plum which settle into a leathery, woody base.\nSize: 50ml | Key notes: Rum, leather, plum, bergamot, milk, amber, patchouli | Shipping: Calculated at checkout\nCustomer experience: “This scent is the perfect mixture of feminine and masculine. The Kakadu plum gives such a unique sweetness to the underlying woody/leather scent,” writes one reviewer.\nByredo\nVelvet Haze eau de parfum\nStockholm-based brand Byredo has gained a cult following for the right reasons. Its unisex range is alluring in its minimalism. We’re particular fans of Velvet Haze, but Byredo Bal D'Afrique is also widely beloved for its intriguing and gender-neutral scent.\nSize: 100ml | Key notes: Coconut, hibiscus, bergamot, patchouli, tuberose, osmanthus, musk, cacao, ambrette | Shipping: Free delivery\nCustomer experience: “A faded memory of the 1960s,” reads one review. Read more reviews here.\nPenhaligon’s\nAlUla EDP\nIconic British perfume house Penhaligon’s has been providing stunning fragrances to the world since the late 1860s. If anyone knows the power and craft of a perfect scent, it’s this brand. This ethos culminates in the unisex AlUla eau de parfum, which evokes images of sand and sky in a blend of amber, spices, plums, incense and balmy vanilla notes.\nSize: 100ml | Key notes: Black pepper, Madagascar plum, turmeric root, cardamom oil, vanilla bean, saffron, tobacco accord, patchouli heart, olibanum oil | Shipping: Free delivery\nCustomer experience: “Gorgeous, gorgeous scent. Opens up with a sharp note, cutting through the spiciness, developing on the skin into a mouthwatering, juicy plum. Sweet, juicy and captivating,” writes one reviewer. Read more reviews here.\nThe Body Shop\nFull Ylang Ylang eau de parfum\nIn The Body Shop's Full Flowers range—a new unisex collection where each fragrance is inspired by the whole flower, including all the flower's gendered parts—the Full Ylang Ylang eau de parfum offers a truly unique and delicious spicy, white floral scent extracted from the ylang ylang flowers of Madagascar. Spritz this scent and discover how it evolves throughout the day.\nSize: 75ml | Key notes: Ylang ylang, black pepper, vanilla | Shipping: Free delivery\nCustomer experience: “I’m obsessed, I won’t be getting any other perfume but this for a long time,” writes one reviewer. Read more reviews here.\nLe Labo\nSantal 33 eau de parfum\nWalking outside your door in 2019 meant an almost guaranteed whiff of Santal 33, and it still does today. One of the most loved unisex fragrances around is popular for good reason—notes of sandalwood, papyrus and cardamom keep it earthy and grounded, while iris and violet elevate its pitch to result in an intoxicating, fluid scent.\nSize: 50ml | Key notes: Cardamon, iris, violet, ambrox, Australian sandalwood, papyrus, cedarwood | Shipping: Free over\nCustomer experience: “It's taken me my whole life to find this amazing fragrance. I've always been a fan of more masculine scents like wood smoke, leather, whisky and old leather jackets,” writes one reviewer. Read more reviews here.\nBoy Smells\nGenderful Violet Ends cologne de parfum\nWithin Boy Smells' Genderful universe, a mix of masculine and feminine scent notes are expertly combined to encourage a sense of duality for the wearer. Within this collection, our standout has to be the powerful Violet Ends—with top notes of rhubarb and bergamot and middle notes of black tea and raw tobacco, held in base notes of white birch and smoked papyrus, this perfume is dark, warm and complex.\nSize: 65ml | Key notes: Rhubarb, bergamot, black pepper, black tea, tobacco leaf, incense, white birch, tanned leather, smoked papyrus | Shipping: $43\nCustomer experience: “Feels like a date night smell,” reads one review. Read more reviews here.\nMaison Francis Kurkdjian\nGentle Fluidity Silver Edition eau de parfum\nThis luxury fragrance by Maison Francis Kurkdjian, aptly named Gentle Fluidity, is a multi-faceted scent created from juniper berries, fragrant spices and warm woody notes, held together by sweet and soothing vanilla—a perfect blend.\nSize: 200ml | Key notes: Juniper berries, nutmeg, coriander, musk, ambery woods, vanilla | Shipping: Approximately $57\nCustomer experience: “Even though this is billed as a masculine leaning fragrance, it's most definitely unisex—just not floral or sweet. One of the best perfumes I've experienced (and I have a LOT), it's quite unlike anything I own: clean, cool spices, icily aquatic, refreshing & undeniably elegant. Basically, this smells like money and expensive gin,” writes one reviewer. Read more reviews here.\nDries Van Noten\nSantal Greenery eau de parfum\nFor an outdoorsy, woody scent that delicately balances the contrasting fragrances of sandalwood and green fig leaf, entangled with white musk, light citrus and florals, no one of any gender could go wrong with Dries Van Noten's Santal Greenery.\nSize: 100ml | Key notes: Bergamot, grapefruit, violet leaves, creamy fig, sandalwood, white musk | Shipping: Approximately $57\nCustomer experience: “The most unisex of the lot,” says one reviewer. Read more reviews here.\nAerway\nKnown for offering engineered functional perfumes that can help to influence your mood, emotion and wellbeing, whilst using unisex olfactory designs, Aerway is a new frontier of fragrance. Connect+ uses a blend of sweet, spiced and woody scents to reduce stress and anxiety—as well as help you smell incredible.\nSize: 50ml | Key notes: Thyme, citrus, pink pepper, chestnut, clove, caramel, vanilla, guaic wood, cedarwood | Shipping: Free delivery\nCustomer experience: “I’m pleasantly surprised by the scent… really fresh which is exactly what I like,” writes one reviewer. Read more reviews here.\nMaison Margiela\nWith a blend of orange blossom flowers, clove oil and chestnut atop a comforting vanilla, this fragrance by the french fashion house and parfumerie is warm and transportive.\nSize: 30ml | Key notes: Pink pepper, orange flower, clove oil, chestnut accord, gaïac wood oil, cade oil, vanilla accord, Peru balsam, cashmeran | Shipping: Free delivery\nCustomer experience: “The perfect après ski scent… The olfactory nostalgia of this perfume is *mwah* chef’s kiss. Evocative of sitting by the fire after a day on the slopes, it’s the perfect scent to transport you to where you’d rather be,” writes one reviewer. Read more reviews here.\nWhat is the difference between gender-neutral and gender fluid perfumes?\nAccording to French perfumer Francis Kurkdijian, founder of the eponymous perfume house, everything. Gender neutral scents have been around for a long time, and are designed to be worn and loved by people identifying as any gender due to their blend of notes that have traditionally been divided between perfumes for men and women respectively.\n“But fluidity doesn’t mean genderless. We have to be very specific in our vocabulary,” explains Kurkdjian. “Gender fluidity means one to another, to be able to transition in a fluid manner. This is very very different [to a unisex fragrance].”\nWhat do unisex fragrances smell like?\nUnisex fragrances, by design, encompass a wide spectrum of scents that defy traditional gender categorisations. They are characterised by their versatility and often feature a balanced blend of notes that appeal to a broad audience. Ranging from fresh and citrusy to woody and musky, they often strike a harmonious balance between floral, spicy, and herbal elements.\nUnisex fragrances tend to be less overtly masculine or feminine, making them suitable for anyone who appreciates a scent that transcends conventional boundaries. Ultimately, the beauty of unisex fragrances lies in their ability to adapt to individual preferences and evoke a sense of timeless elegance that appeals to a diverse range of individuals.\nWhere do I buy unisex perfumes?\nUnisex perfumes are becoming more and more common. According to a new products survey done by Mintel, gender-neutral fragrance releases made up 17 per cent of the market in 2010, and by 2018 that figure had ballooned to 51 per cent.\nYou might have grown up spritzing perfumes on at department stores, but now, many of us are shopping online for our scents. Adore Beauty stocks a whole range, including Aesop, Amouage and Who Is Elijah, while make-up stores like Sephora and Mecca have dedicated fragrance sections. For international fragrances that can be hard to source in stores across Australia, major international online retailers like Sense and Selfridges can also be a great option.\nOriginally published as Fluid form: 18 unisex fragrances for universal appeal"}
{"id": "c9_b_00444", "url": "https://www.insidermonkey.com/blog/15-countries-that-have-the-best-weather-in-africa-1209307/", "time": "2023-11-01", "title": "15 Countries that Have the Best Weather in Africa", "text": "In this article, we will take a look at the 15 countries that have the best weather in Africa.\nWhen some people think about Africa, their thoughts often gravitate toward themes of conflict, crime, disease, corruption, poverty, and the label, dark continent. Yet, many people may overlook the fact that it is the presence of darkness that allows the brilliance of light to shine. Africa stands as the second-largest and second-most-populous continent globally, comprising 54 diverse nations, each possessing its unique splendor.\nAfrica offers a rich tapestry of natural wonders, from the captivating beauty of its savannahs and numerous national parks and reserves to its vast deserts like the Sahara and Namib. The continent boasts an array of majestic rivers, including the Zambezi, Rovuma, Okavango, Congo, Niger, Luangwa, Nile, and Tugela. Its stunning lakes, such as Malawi, Victoria, Turkana, and Tanganyika, grace its landscapes. Africa is also adorned with imposing mountains like the Drakensberg, Mount Kenya, and Kilimanjaro. To top it off, the continent is a culinary paradise with a diverse array of foods. Additionally, Africa is renowned as the home of the Animal Kingdom, where the abundance of food sources supports a rich variety of wildlife.\nAfrica’s climate encompasses a wide array of types, including the equatorial climate, tropical wet and dry climate, tropical monsoon climate, semi-desert climate, desert climate, and subtropical highland climate, among others. Temperate climates are a rarity on the continent, confined mainly to elevated areas and coastal regions. Remarkably, Africa’s climate is more influenced by variable rainfall patterns than by temperature fluctuations, which consistently remain high. The continent’s deserts, particularly, stand out as the sunniest and driest regions, owing to the persistent presence of the subtropical ridge, which ushers in hot, arid air masses. Africa boasts numerous heat-related records, holding distinctions for having the hottest extended region year-round, the areas with the hottest summer climates, and the highest duration of sunshine, among others.\nIn North Africa, an arid desert climate prevails, characterized by scorching temperatures and minimal rainfall, with occasional nighttime freezing temperatures in mountainous and Sahara regions. Equatorial West and Central Africa, on the other hand, experience a monsoon climate, marked by elevated temperatures, soaring humidity levels, and substantial seasonal downpours. In East Africa, distinct dry and rainy seasons are observed, while Southern Africa typically enjoys a more temperate climate.\nAfrica’s climatic diversity is a result of its expansive presence across equatorial and subtropical latitudes in both the northern and southern hemispheres. Situated primarily within the intertropical zone, bounded by the Tropic of Cancer and the Tropic of Capricorn, the continent maintains consistently high humidity levels, making it predominantly hot. Warm and hot climates are prevalent throughout Africa, with the northern region characterized by arid conditions and high temperatures. Mediterranean climates, akin to those found along the northernmost and southernmost fringes of the continent, are exceptions to this rule. The equator, along with the Tropic of Cancer and the Tropic of Capricorn, bisects Africa, earning it the distinction of being the world’s most tropical continent.\nIn many African countries, the progression of seasons diverges from the typical pattern observed in Europe and the United States. Rather than experiencing the familiar spring, summer, fall, and winter cycles, most countries situated south of the Sahara Desert are characterized by distinct dry and rainy seasons. This phenomenon is particularly pronounced in equatorial countries, where temperatures remain consistently warm throughout the year, yet the volume of precipitation undergoes dramatic fluctuations. Northern regions of Africa which includes Morocco, Algeria, Tunisia, and Libya, undergo winter conditions from December to March, while the southern areas of South Africa encounter winter from June to September. But also, there are some African countries with good weather all year round.\nThe weather on the elevated plateaus of numerous East African countries is favored by both residents and tourists, often regarded as the finest. The majority of capital cities in these countries are situated at altitudes exceeding 1400 meters. Take, for instance, Kigali, Kampala, Nairobi, and Addis Ababa. Daytime temperatures seldom surpass 30 degrees Celsius, and nights offer cool, comfortable conditions for sleeping. Thanks to the elevation, the climate is also relatively low in humidity. Meanwhile, if you’re thinking about which country has the best climate in the world, you can take a look at our other article.\nOur Methodology\nIn this article, we will be answering the question, “Which country has the best weather in Africa?” To compile our list of the 15 countries that have the best weather in Africa, we performed comprehensive research and collated data from various distinct sources. Each time a country was referenced in these sources along with its average surface air temperature and feedback from locals and tourists, we assigned a specific point. By calculating the average scores derived from these criteria, we crafted our selection of the 15 countries that have the best weather in Africa.\n15 Countries that Have the Best Weather in Africa\n15. Botswana\nRanking 15th in our list of the countries that have the best weather in Africa is Botswana. Botswana’s climate is classified as semi-arid. While a significant portion of the year is characterized by hot and arid conditions, there is a distinct rainy season that spans the summer months. During this season, rain tends to manifest episodically, without a clear pattern, and varies greatly from one region to another.\n14. Mozambique\nMozambique experiences a tropical to sub-tropical climate. The dry season spans from April to December, featuring temperatures ranging from 25°C to 33°C. In contrast, the wet season extends from January to March, with temperatures slightly elevated, ranging from 30°C to 33°C. Rainfall in Mozambique exhibits a north-to-south gradient, with higher precipitation levels along the coastal regions, where the annual average typically ranges from 800 to 1200 mm.\n13. Rwanda\nRwanda ranks 13th in our list of countries that have the best weather in Africa. Rwanda is situated only two degrees south of the equator; however, its considerable elevation results in a delightful tropical highland climate. Rwanda’s mean annual temperature stands at 19.1℃, with monthly averages fluctuating between 19.5°C in September and 18.5℃ in July. The yearly rainfall amounts to 1,170.2 mm. In contrast to many African countries located farther from the equator, Rwanda enjoys a climate that is neither excessively hot nor overly cold.\n12. Cape Verde\nThe best period to explore Cape Verde falls between November and June, allowing you to fully enjoy the renowned white-sand beaches that grace the islands. During this time, temperatures typically range from the mid-to-high twenties, and precipitation is minimal. Cape Verde exhibits a relatively narrow annual temperature range, with coastal areas maintaining an average temperature of approximately 25ºC, while regions above 1,000 meters reach around 19ºC. The lowest temperature values, ranging from 20ºC to 21ºC, are observed from January to April, whereas the highest values of 26ºC to 28ºC occur in August and September.\n11. Algeria\nRanking 11th in our list of countries that have the best weather in Africa is Algeria. Algeria experiences two contrasting climatic regions. First is the Mediterranean climate in the northern part of the country and then a desert climate that predominates across the majority of its territory. The coastal and Tell Atlas Mountains regions experience a sub-humid Mediterranean climate, marked by relatively wet and mild winters, as well as hot and dry summers. In the remainder of the country, the vast Sahara Desert takes over, with seasonal average winter temperatures ranging from 15°C to 28°C and soaring to 40°C to 45°C during the summer. In the northern areas, humid winds from the sea usher in precipitation from autumn through spring.\n10. Madagascar\nMadagascar is often included in the top 10 best African countries to live in. Madagascar experiences two distinct seasons which are a warm, rainy season stretching from November to April and a cooler, drier season that spans from May to October. Along the eastern coast, the climate is sub-equatorial, influenced by easterly trade winds, and it receives the highest and most consistent rainfall, averaging up to 3,700 mm annually. Generally, the period from April to October is considered the best time to visit Madagascar. This is the dry and cool season, often referred to as the austral winter by naturalists. During this period, travel conditions are quite favorable, with bright and typically warm to very warm days and mild nights.\n9. Namibia\nNamibia ranks 9th in our list of countries that have the best weather in Africa. The ideal period for a Namibia visit falls between July and October when temperatures hover slightly above 21°C, and the likelihood of rainfall is minimal. This span coincides with prime wildlife viewing, marking the peak of the travel season. During this time, the skies remain clear, the risk of malaria is at its lowest, and as the dry season progresses, animals become more concentrated around water sources.\n8. Zambia\nZambia secured the 8th spot in our list of countries that have the best weather in Africa. For Zambia, the best time for a visit falls within the dry season, spanning from June to November. During this time, expect vivid blue skies, warm days, and cooler nights, with temperatures ranging from 23°C to 36°C throughout the country. This season also offers abundant opportunities for wildlife observation. Zambia experiences a predominantly warm climate, with an annual average temperature of 29°C. However, there are only a few months with a genuinely tropical and humid feel.\n7. Morocco\nThe most favorable times to explore Morocco are during the autumn and spring seasons. Nevertheless, Morocco’s diverse geography offers unique charms in each season. Overall, the country boasts a tropical climate, with temperatures ranging from a high of 35°C to a low of 5°C in the Sahara region. Along the coast, you’ll encounter a warm, Mediterranean climate, softened on the eastern coast by southwest trade winds, while the inland areas feature a hotter, drier, continental climate.\n6. Tanzania\nTanzania bagged the 6th spot in our list of countries that have the best weather in Africa. Tanzania boasts a consistently pleasant climate throughout the year, although notable regional differences exist. The tropical climate in Tanzania varies according to the region and elevation. Coastal areas tend to be hot and humid, while the low-lying parks offer drier and cooler conditions. The best time for a Tanzania visit is during the dry season, spanning from July to October, aligning with the Great Wildebeest Migration.\n5. Zimbabwe\nThe best time for a trip to Zimbabwe falls within the window from July to October when wildlife observation is at its zenith. During this period, the natural waterholes in the parks dry up, drawing substantial herds to the lakes, man-made waterholes, and rivers. Zimbabwe experiences a subtropical climate with extended, hot summers featuring average temperatures around 30°C, and comparatively cooler winters, often marked by notably cooler nighttime temperatures.\n4. Ethiopia\nRanking 4th in our list of countries that have the best weather in Africa is Ethiopia. Ethiopia’s climate displays a tropical character in the lowland areas of the southeastern and northeastern regions, whereas it becomes notably cooler in the expansive central highland areas. The average annual temperatures tend to range from 15-20˚C in the higher-altitude regions and 25-30˚C in the lowlands. The most favorable period to visit is from October to June when the dry season prevails. Rains typically cease early in October, resulting in lush and green highlands, providing an ideal setting for trekking amid the vibrant wildflowers that have bloomed."}
{"id": "c9_b_00446", "url": "https://thewest.com.au/travel/travel-year-in-review-2023-c-12790762", "time": "2023-12-30", "title": "Travel Year in Review, 2023", "text": "The year began with me sitting in a strange metal tube that was vibrating and humming, with people bringing me food. Watching a movie, and another movie, and another movie. Me in that strange metal tube, with the world moving underneath it, way down, 40,000 feet beneath me.\nYes, the year began in an aeroplane.\nImagine that — being out in the world. And how.\nThis year I have travelled to Singapore, New York City, Adelaide, the UK, Botswana, Zimbabwe, Zambia, the Bungle Bungle, New Norcia, Norway, the Faroe Islands, Iceland, Ireland, Morocco, Qatar, the UK (again), Singapore (again) and India.\nAnd, for the rest of the Travel team, Vietnam, Cambodia, Japan, the USA, Mauritius, New Zealand… you name it.\nWe have been busy back out in the world, representing you, the reader; writing for you, the reader — in first person, present tense, so you see the world through our eyes exactly as we see the world.\nUSA\nThe year started with the world’s longest flight, from Singapore to New York City — 17 hours with Singapore Airlines in an ultra-long range A350-900. What a fitting way to start this big year of international travel, with a lap of the globe.\nFrom Singapore, we fly east past Vietnam and the Philippines, east of Japan and then Kamchatka Peninsula in Russia’s far east (where I’ve watched bears fishing for salmon). We cross the Bering Sea, fly over Alaska, the Great Lakes and then south to New York City.\nNew York in winter is a cold city full of black puffer jackets and beanies, and always the threat of snow. Start with a good breakfast, on one of the little row of pedestal stools in Johnys diner, off Seventh Avenue. Old-style, welcoming New York.\nThe trip home completes the lap of the planet — flying up, off the Newfoundland coast, over the Arctic, past Iceland and then up the English Channel, over France, Turkey, Iran, India and back to Singapore.\nNow, that was one wild ride.\nADELAIDE\nIn Adelaide it’s baking hot and I’m booted and suited for the big occasion — my son Max’s marriage to Connie. We travel for all sorts of reasons, don’t we, and that is the best trip of the year, for all the obvious reasons.\nBut then straight off to the UK for a last visit to my ailing mother. To farewell her. I think it will be the worst trip of the year, but she has lucid moments; good moments. We travel for all sorts of reasons, don’t we, and are rewarded in all sorts of ways.\nAFRICA\nAt 8am on the first day in Botswana we’re sitting in the low sunshine watching a pride of lions pose and position themselves in artfully landscaped fallen timber — the perfect photographic set-up in perfect light.\nYeah, that’s how the day started in Machaba, in the Okavango Delta, and after a succession of sightings (zebra, giraffe, hippo, elephants galore, the big five and more) it ended like this… in the dark, in the vehicles, heading back to the bush camp and me thinking “the only thing missing is a leopard, it’d be nice to see a leopard”, and as we come round a bend in the single lane track, there in the headlights in the middle of that single-lane track, is a leopard (and a beauty).\nMy friend Grady videos it walking up to and past our vehicle. I see the leopard’s coat turn red in the tail lights and you can hear my wife Virginia, on that video, saying: “That’s a bit too close”.\nAt Victoria Falls, we walk out on the Knifedge Bridge and stand in the centre of the almost-complete circle of a rainbow, happily soaked by rain coming upwards as much as down.\nI love the Zambian side of the falls not just for this, but for the town of Livingstone, which is named for Dr David Livingstone. In the town’s museum, I stand in front of his coat and hat — and his actual medical chest.\n(I must add, that while we’re away our dog Shackleton dies, her ashes on the mantelpiece next to Lasseter’s, and we now have a new rescue pup called Livingstone.)\nIn all the revisions of the colonial era and of the slavery that started among African tribes and was exploited by Arabs and then Europeans, Dr Livingstone’s reputation remains intact, and he remains loved across Africa, including here in this town of Livingstone.\nI love Livingstone for its Mukuni market with shops full of colourful waxed cotton and wigs and lollies spread out on cardboard and sold individually and in pairs and threes.\nAnd I love crossing over to the Zimbabwe side of the falls (mainly to kayak on the Zambezi River). I always instantly feel happy in Zimbabwe, just because of the people here. They are welcoming. They are kind. They are funny. They are happy, despite all that’s happened since independence in 1980, living under the Robert Mugabe regime, the endemic corruption, inflation which hit 1000 per cent a year in the 2000s and having not a cent of government support during the pandemic. They were so lacking in medicines that they boiled leaves and ground roots as bush remedies.\nBut they remain happy, welcoming people. My new friend Presha Ncube tells me: “It is our motto to see the best in things. To be happy (well, that’s a good motto).”\nKIMBERLEY\nIn the Kimberley next, I’m in the Bungle Bungle for the 20th anniversary of Purnululu’s World Heritage status, and the opening of its new Visitor Centre.\nI am walking into Cathedral Gorge with Gidja man Paul Butters, who lives in Frog Hollow. We just hit it off.\nPaul says: “I think we’re a bit the same you and me — a little bit fun, a little bit feral, a little bit rogue, a little bit ratbag, but good at heart.”\nI travel on all sorts of formal assignments, but the personal always sneaks in.\nNORWAY\nAt 11.10pm on my first night in Bergen, a mighty thunderclap directly overhead slaps the pretty little Norwegian coastal town, right out of the blue. The great Norse god Thor, god of thunder, making himself known.\nNorway is a land of powerful landscapes, which power myths as much as they power the hydro electric generators invisible inside mountains which produce its “100 per cent green” power.\nI’m in the fjords, Geiranger and Flam, and in historic towns, Alesund and Bergen, and I’m thinking about fish. Cod was the Vikings’ greatest weapon — greater than the broadsword. When they learnt to dry fish, on wooden racks in the salty coastal air, keeping nutrients intact, they gave themselves the freedom to sail further.\nAnd I follow in their wake to the Faroe Islands, with the oldest functioning parliament in the world, which they called the Thing (yes, there was a Thing before there was a thing).\nAnd I travel on east, to Iceland, to paddle kayaks in Isafjordur, dwarfed by huge landscapes, thinking of the great gods who can shake us to the core.\nMOROCCO\nAt 11.10pm on my last night in Morocco, the hotel starts to shake.\nFor the first 10 seconds, I’m pretty nervy, as I think it might be a bomb, but when the building continues to shake violently I calm down, realising it’s an earthquake, which is a better option. I’d rather face nature than terrorists any day.\nI run down the stairwell and stand away from the building in the cool night. I hear the sirens and news that places I’ve just been in Marrakesh and the High Atlas Mountains are now just rubble.\nThere are messages from my brother when I land back in Perth (my faithful suitcase Casey somewhere behind me, making his own way home). My brother Rob isn’t just asking about my wellbeing — he’s telling me that Mother has died. So I turn round and fly back to England. We travel for all sorts of reasons and are tested and rewarded in all sorts of ways.\nOn one of my last outings with Mother, we watched buzzards flying over a churchyard, and I can see her face, looking up, smiling, enthralled. In that moment, it seemed to me, she was as free as the birds soaring in the blue sky above her, and it seems to me that is the feeling I have when I travel.\nINDIA\nI certainly felt that footloose freedom in India, just a few days ago, enjoying the crazy-busy everyday of some of my favourite places. Agra and the Taj Mahal, full of colourful locals visiting at the end of Diwali, the festival of light. Jaipur, the pink city with its beautiful Amber Fort. Udaipur, this more gentle city of white palaces set around a blue lake.\nI love being in India.\nI love the intensity, the humanity, the honesty, the colour, the challenges, the rewards, the intimacy and elaborateness of thinking — all that richness, all that poverty, the rub and contradiction and the demands of it all.\nThis is life in 3D. This is life in vivid colour. This is life with humour.\nOn the day after Australia’s win over India in the Cricket World Cup final, I’m standing with tuk-tuk drivers negotiating, planning things, working things out. When we have concluded our dealings, I say: “I suppose you’d like a tip.” Of course they nod. Tipping is part of the culture. It cements relationships. It lubricates society. It makes things run smoothly.\n“I’ll give you a tip,” I say. “Score more runs in the cricket next time.” And then slip them 500 rupees each, hidden in a handshake.\nULURU\nBut the year isn’t over, and next comes the vivid colour of Uluru for New Year’s Eve.\nWhere better to end this year of joy and sadness, of the full range of emotions, of weddings and funerals, than with Virginia in the beating heart of Australia, feeling the pulse of the planet.\nGet the latest news from thewest.com.au in your inbox.\nSign up for our emails"}
{"id": "c9_b_00443", "url": "https://www.couriermail.com.au/lifestyle/best-unisex-perfumes/news-story/c3034b9034987f3a8feb7351c84b2c29?nk=489e34a044bc2da193e49588439109ec-1700384507", "time": "2024-06-26", "title": "Fluid form: 18 unisex fragrances for universal appeal", "text": "Fluid form: 18 unisex fragrances for universal appeal\nFrom Byredo to Le Labo to Who Is Elijah, here are our picks of the best unisex perfumes that don’t conform.\nFrom Byredo to Le Labo to Who Is Elijah, here are our picks of the best unisex perfumes that don’t conform.\nVogue Australia may receive advertising or affiliate commission if you buy through our links. Read more here.\nHers, mine, yours, theirs. Fragrance has long moved beyond the realm of binary gender to embrace a fluid way of being: gone are the strict delineations between florals and musk for women and spice and woodiness for men. We’re complex, our tastes are varied, and our fragrances will be too across all top, middle and base notes.\nStrangely enough, the gender divide in the fragrance world is a relatively recent invention. In the Middle Ages, fragrances were drawn from natural sources—flowers, wood—to mask natural odours in men and women, until marketing in the late 20th century began to emphasise the distinctions between genders. But in the mid-1990s, Calvin Klein's CK One, a now-iconic unisex scent, entered the fragrance cosmos: it heralded a bold new era, where a clean, striking scent profile could be worn by anyone and signature scents had to be neither inherently masculine or feminine.\nNow, Australian brands are also joining the international game. Who Is Elijah, the cult favourite you’re seeing all over Instagram packages up sexy, enigmatic scents in sparse, minimal bottles for an all-round sensory experience. Mihan Aromatics, designed by a Fitzroy couple, also has a four-product range of fragrances designed to mimic the smells and surrounds of the pair’s home, and of their favourite local haunts.\nBelow, our picks of the best unisex and gender-neutral fragrances to shop right now.\nVogue’s top picks\n- Best luxury unisex fragrance: Byredo Velvet Haze eau de parfum\n- Best affordable unisex fragrance: Calvin Klein CK One eau de toilette\n- Best Australian unisex fragrance: Who Is Elijah His | Her\n- Best floral unisex fragrance: Full Ylang Ylang eau de parfum\n- Best spice unisex fragrance: Aesop Hwyl eau de parfum\nThe best unisex, gender-neutral fragrances of 2024\nWho Is Elijah\nHis | Her\nWith sweet, spicy top notes sitting on a bed of verdant freshness, Australian label Who Is Elijah makes the ultimate go-between scent—and, what's more, the female-owned and run brand takes its clean credentials seriously.\nSize: 100ml | Key notes: Bergamot, violet leaf, cardamom, fir needle, sandalwood, cashmere musk | Shipping: Free delivery\nCustomer experience: “I love the scent so much I bought another bottle… It smells sophisticated and I get heaps of compliments. It wears long/strong and I still get hints of it at the end of the day,” one customer writes. Read more reviews here.\nJo Malone London\nLondon Wood Sage & Sea Salt cologne\nFrom fragrance powerhouse Jo Malone London, this earthy sage and wood forward cologne mixed with fresh sea salt evokes a windswept coastal shore, breaking waves and rugged cliffs, making it a perfect neutral scent for the spring and summer months.\nSize: 50ml | Key notes: Ambrette seeds, sea salt, sage | Shipping: Free delivery\nCustomer experience: “This is summer in a bottle,” writes one reviewer. Read more reviews here.\nAmouage\nMeander eau de parfum\nReleased in 2020, Amouage’s jade bottle with a stone-studded neck hides a complex, layered fragrance. It pays homage to the monsoon season in the plateaus of Oman, the brand’s home country, with spicy, woody notes that stay green and springy.\nSize: 100ml | Key notes: Olibanum oil, carrot heart, pink pepper, black pepper oil, orris, rose, cypriol Heart, vetiver oil | Shipping: Free delivery\nCustomer experience: “This fragrance is beautiful and unique. It’s quite gentle and I find that the opening fades into the mid very quickly on my skin. The opening to me feels almost as if you’re eating a lavender and green tea flavoured desert. I also get a slight hint of pepper shortly after spraying but it isn’t overbearing at all. This fragrance is completely unisex to me but I find this to be a particularly gentlemanly fragrance,” one reviewer writes. Read more reviews here.\nMihan Aromatics\nMikado Bark parfum\nMelbourne-based perfumers Mihan Aromatics have created a scant, clean line of fragrances utilising native ingredients with reserve and grace. This one brings back the scent of the Fitzroy Gardens on long summer evenings.\nSize: 100ml | Key notes: Green pepper, rosemary, basil, dry cinnamon, oud, sandalwood, wet cedar | Shipping: Free delivery\nCustomer experience: “This scent is wonderful! Not too sweet, not too woody, but a nice mix of the two and a bit earthy,” one reviewer writes. Read more reviews here.\nCalvin Klein\nCK One eau de toilette\nNo gender-neutral fragrance list would be complete without the scent that hung in the air throughout the late 1990s. This iconic option by Calvin Klein is clean, youthful and citrus-laden.\nSize: 100ml | Key notes: Green tea, bergamot, cardamon, violet, rose, nutmeg, amber, musk | Shipping: Free delivery over $99\nCustomer experience: “This spray is so beautiful! It's not too overpowering but it has a nice, fresh and clean scent. Perfect for both me and my partner to use,” writes one reviewer. Read more reviews here.\nAesop\nHwyl eau de parfum\nKnown for its earthy, unorthodox formulations, Aesop brings you a smoky, spicy medley of a fragrance in Hwyl—with warm heart notes flecked with vetiver, thyme and moss, this fragrances hints at a unisex floral scent without the sweetness.\nSize: 50ml | Key notes: Thyme, elemi, nutmeg, cypress, geranium, suede, vetiver, cedarwood, patchouli | Shipping: Free delivery\nCustomer experience: “This perfume has been my signature scent for a year now. It's rich and earthy, I love it,” writes one reviewer. Read more reviews here.\nBDK Parfums\nVelvet Tonka eau de parfum\nA fragrance that is sometimes bitter and sometimes sweet as it evolves throughout the wear, inspired by the smells of Morocco and the Atlas Mountains, and a symbol of unisex sensuality with a slight feminine lean, Velvet Tonka by BDK Parfums is a unique, powdery and vintage scent.\nSize: 100ml | Key notes: Orange blossom, almond, rose absolute, tobacco absolute, vanilla absolute, amyris wood essence, amber woods | Shipping: Free delivery\nCustomer experience: “This beautiful perfume is the most gorgeous perfume. It smells utterly sweet and divine. I cannot get enough of it. I get so many compliments when I wear it,” writes one reviewer. Read more reviews here.\nClarins\nEau Dynamisante treatment fragrance\nLeading with sweet and bitter orange, combined with lavandin and eucalyptus and followed by patchouli, Eau Dynamisante by Clarins boasts a fresh, light aroma as well as a stimulating and energising effect on the skin—turning this natural, citrus forward fragrance into a multi-use product.\nSize: 100ml | Key notes: Sweet and bitter orange, mandarin, petitgrain, lavandin, eucalyptus, tarragon, nutmeg, patchouli | Shipping: Free delivery\nCustomer experience: “This is the scent of white linen and a cool breeze,” reads one review. Read more reviews here.\nMalin + Goetz\nDark Rum eau de parfum\nLiquor me up. This dark, sultry fragrance features top notes of bergamot and plum which settle into a leathery, woody base.\nSize: 50ml | Key notes: Rum, leather, plum, bergamot, milk, amber, patchouli | Shipping: Calculated at checkout\nCustomer experience: “This scent is the perfect mixture of feminine and masculine. The Kakadu plum gives such a unique sweetness to the underlying woody/leather scent,” writes one reviewer.\nByredo\nVelvet Haze eau de parfum\nStockholm-based brand Byredo has gained a cult following for the right reasons. Its unisex range is alluring in its minimalism. We’re particular fans of Velvet Haze, but Byredo Bal D'Afrique is also widely beloved for its intriguing and gender-neutral scent.\nSize: 100ml | Key notes: Coconut, hibiscus, bergamot, patchouli, tuberose, osmanthus, musk, cacao, ambrette | Shipping: Free delivery\nCustomer experience: “A faded memory of the 1960s,” reads one review. Read more reviews here.\nPenhaligon’s\nAlUla EDP\nIconic British perfume house Penhaligon’s has been providing stunning fragrances to the world since the late 1860s. If anyone knows the power and craft of a perfect scent, it’s this brand. This ethos culminates in the unisex AlUla eau de parfum, which evokes images of sand and sky in a blend of amber, spices, plums, incense and balmy vanilla notes.\nSize: 100ml | Key notes: Black pepper, Madagascar plum, turmeric root, cardamom oil, vanilla bean, saffron, tobacco accord, patchouli heart, olibanum oil | Shipping: Free delivery\nCustomer experience: “Gorgeous, gorgeous scent. Opens up with a sharp note, cutting through the spiciness, developing on the skin into a mouthwatering, juicy plum. Sweet, juicy and captivating,” writes one reviewer. Read more reviews here.\nThe Body Shop\nFull Ylang Ylang eau de parfum\nIn The Body Shop's Full Flowers range—a new unisex collection where each fragrance is inspired by the whole flower, including all the flower's gendered parts—the Full Ylang Ylang eau de parfum offers a truly unique and delicious spicy, white floral scent extracted from the ylang ylang flowers of Madagascar. Spritz this scent and discover how it evolves throughout the day.\nSize: 75ml | Key notes: Ylang ylang, black pepper, vanilla | Shipping: Free delivery\nCustomer experience: “I’m obsessed, I won’t be getting any other perfume but this for a long time,” writes one reviewer. Read more reviews here.\nLe Labo\nSantal 33 eau de parfum\nWalking outside your door in 2019 meant an almost guaranteed whiff of Santal 33, and it still does today. One of the most loved unisex fragrances around is popular for good reason—notes of sandalwood, papyrus and cardamom keep it earthy and grounded, while iris and violet elevate its pitch to result in an intoxicating, fluid scent.\nSize: 50ml | Key notes: Cardamon, iris, violet, ambrox, Australian sandalwood, papyrus, cedarwood | Shipping: Free over\nCustomer experience: “It's taken me my whole life to find this amazing fragrance. I've always been a fan of more masculine scents like wood smoke, leather, whisky and old leather jackets,” writes one reviewer. Read more reviews here.\nBoy Smells\nGenderful Violet Ends cologne de parfum\nWithin Boy Smells' Genderful universe, a mix of masculine and feminine scent notes are expertly combined to encourage a sense of duality for the wearer. Within this collection, our standout has to be the powerful Violet Ends—with top notes of rhubarb and bergamot and middle notes of black tea and raw tobacco, held in base notes of white birch and smoked papyrus, this perfume is dark, warm and complex.\nSize: 65ml | Key notes: Rhubarb, bergamot, black pepper, black tea, tobacco leaf, incense, white birch, tanned leather, smoked papyrus | Shipping: $43\nCustomer experience: “Feels like a date night smell,” reads one review. Read more reviews here.\nMaison Francis Kurkdjian\nGentle Fluidity Silver Edition eau de parfum\nThis luxury fragrance by Maison Francis Kurkdjian, aptly named Gentle Fluidity, is a multi-faceted scent created from juniper berries, fragrant spices and warm woody notes, held together by sweet and soothing vanilla—a perfect blend.\nSize: 200ml | Key notes: Juniper berries, nutmeg, coriander, musk, ambery woods, vanilla | Shipping: Approximately $57\nCustomer experience: “Even though this is billed as a masculine leaning fragrance, it's most definitely unisex—just not floral or sweet. One of the best perfumes I've experienced (and I have a LOT), it's quite unlike anything I own: clean, cool spices, icily aquatic, refreshing & undeniably elegant. Basically, this smells like money and expensive gin,” writes one reviewer. Read more reviews here.\nDries Van Noten\nSantal Greenery eau de parfum\nFor an outdoorsy, woody scent that delicately balances the contrasting fragrances of sandalwood and green fig leaf, entangled with white musk, light citrus and florals, no one of any gender could go wrong with Dries Van Noten's Santal Greenery.\nSize: 100ml | Key notes: Bergamot, grapefruit, violet leaves, creamy fig, sandalwood, white musk | Shipping: Approximately $57\nCustomer experience: “The most unisex of the lot,” says one reviewer. Read more reviews here.\nAerway\nKnown for offering engineered functional perfumes that can help to influence your mood, emotion and wellbeing, whilst using unisex olfactory designs, Aerway is a new frontier of fragrance. Connect+ uses a blend of sweet, spiced and woody scents to reduce stress and anxiety—as well as help you smell incredible.\nSize: 50ml | Key notes: Thyme, citrus, pink pepper, chestnut, clove, caramel, vanilla, guaic wood, cedarwood | Shipping: Free delivery\nCustomer experience: “I’m pleasantly surprised by the scent… really fresh which is exactly what I like,” writes one reviewer. Read more reviews here.\nMaison Margiela\nWith a blend of orange blossom flowers, clove oil and chestnut atop a comforting vanilla, this fragrance by the french fashion house and parfumerie is warm and transportive.\nSize: 30ml | Key notes: Pink pepper, orange flower, clove oil, chestnut accord, gaïac wood oil, cade oil, vanilla accord, Peru balsam, cashmeran | Shipping: Free delivery\nCustomer experience: “The perfect après ski scent… The olfactory nostalgia of this perfume is *mwah* chef’s kiss. Evocative of sitting by the fire after a day on the slopes, it’s the perfect scent to transport you to where you’d rather be,” writes one reviewer. Read more reviews here.\nWhat is the difference between gender-neutral and gender fluid perfumes?\nAccording to French perfumer Francis Kurkdijian, founder of the eponymous perfume house, everything. Gender neutral scents have been around for a long time, and are designed to be worn and loved by people identifying as any gender due to their blend of notes that have traditionally been divided between perfumes for men and women respectively.\n“But fluidity doesn’t mean genderless. We have to be very specific in our vocabulary,” explains Kurkdjian. “Gender fluidity means one to another, to be able to transition in a fluid manner. This is very very different [to a unisex fragrance].”\nWhat do unisex fragrances smell like?\nUnisex fragrances, by design, encompass a wide spectrum of scents that defy traditional gender categorisations. They are characterised by their versatility and often feature a balanced blend of notes that appeal to a broad audience. Ranging from fresh and citrusy to woody and musky, they often strike a harmonious balance between floral, spicy, and herbal elements.\nUnisex fragrances tend to be less overtly masculine or feminine, making them suitable for anyone who appreciates a scent that transcends conventional boundaries. Ultimately, the beauty of unisex fragrances lies in their ability to adapt to individual preferences and evoke a sense of timeless elegance that appeals to a diverse range of individuals.\nWhere do I buy unisex perfumes?\nUnisex perfumes are becoming more and more common. According to a new products survey done by Mintel, gender-neutral fragrance releases made up 17 per cent of the market in 2010, and by 2018 that figure had ballooned to 51 per cent.\nYou might have grown up spritzing perfumes on at department stores, but now, many of us are shopping online for our scents. Adore Beauty stocks a whole range, including Aesop, Amouage and Who Is Elijah, while make-up stores like Sephora and Mecca have dedicated fragrance sections. For international fragrances that can be hard to source in stores across Australia, major international online retailers like Sense and Selfridges can also be a great option.\nOriginally published as Fluid form: 18 unisex fragrances for universal appeal"}
{"id": "c9_b_00442", "url": "https://www.couriermail.com.au/lifestyle/best-unisex-perfumes/news-story/c3034b9034987f3a8feb7351c84b2c29?nk=47a86910e5d397414fbca0df47cd4c8b-1700378196", "time": "2024-06-26", "title": "Fluid form: 18 unisex fragrances for universal appeal", "text": "Fluid form: 18 unisex fragrances for universal appeal\nFrom Byredo to Le Labo to Who Is Elijah, here are our picks of the best unisex perfumes that don’t conform.\nFrom Byredo to Le Labo to Who Is Elijah, here are our picks of the best unisex perfumes that don’t conform.\nVogue Australia may receive advertising or affiliate commission if you buy through our links. Read more here.\nHers, mine, yours, theirs. Fragrance has long moved beyond the realm of binary gender to embrace a fluid way of being: gone are the strict delineations between florals and musk for women and spice and woodiness for men. We’re complex, our tastes are varied, and our fragrances will be too across all top, middle and base notes.\nStrangely enough, the gender divide in the fragrance world is a relatively recent invention. In the Middle Ages, fragrances were drawn from natural sources—flowers, wood—to mask natural odours in men and women, until marketing in the late 20th century began to emphasise the distinctions between genders. But in the mid-1990s, Calvin Klein's CK One, a now-iconic unisex scent, entered the fragrance cosmos: it heralded a bold new era, where a clean, striking scent profile could be worn by anyone and signature scents had to be neither inherently masculine or feminine.\nNow, Australian brands are also joining the international game. Who Is Elijah, the cult favourite you’re seeing all over Instagram packages up sexy, enigmatic scents in sparse, minimal bottles for an all-round sensory experience. Mihan Aromatics, designed by a Fitzroy couple, also has a four-product range of fragrances designed to mimic the smells and surrounds of the pair’s home, and of their favourite local haunts.\nBelow, our picks of the best unisex and gender-neutral fragrances to shop right now.\nVogue’s top picks\n- Best luxury unisex fragrance: Byredo Velvet Haze eau de parfum\n- Best affordable unisex fragrance: Calvin Klein CK One eau de toilette\n- Best Australian unisex fragrance: Who Is Elijah His | Her\n- Best floral unisex fragrance: Full Ylang Ylang eau de parfum\n- Best spice unisex fragrance: Aesop Hwyl eau de parfum\nThe best unisex, gender-neutral fragrances of 2024\nWho Is Elijah\nHis | Her\nWith sweet, spicy top notes sitting on a bed of verdant freshness, Australian label Who Is Elijah makes the ultimate go-between scent—and, what's more, the female-owned and run brand takes its clean credentials seriously.\nSize: 100ml | Key notes: Bergamot, violet leaf, cardamom, fir needle, sandalwood, cashmere musk | Shipping: Free delivery\nCustomer experience: “I love the scent so much I bought another bottle… It smells sophisticated and I get heaps of compliments. It wears long/strong and I still get hints of it at the end of the day,” one customer writes. Read more reviews here.\nJo Malone London\nLondon Wood Sage & Sea Salt cologne\nFrom fragrance powerhouse Jo Malone London, this earthy sage and wood forward cologne mixed with fresh sea salt evokes a windswept coastal shore, breaking waves and rugged cliffs, making it a perfect neutral scent for the spring and summer months.\nSize: 50ml | Key notes: Ambrette seeds, sea salt, sage | Shipping: Free delivery\nCustomer experience: “This is summer in a bottle,” writes one reviewer. Read more reviews here.\nAmouage\nMeander eau de parfum\nReleased in 2020, Amouage’s jade bottle with a stone-studded neck hides a complex, layered fragrance. It pays homage to the monsoon season in the plateaus of Oman, the brand’s home country, with spicy, woody notes that stay green and springy.\nSize: 100ml | Key notes: Olibanum oil, carrot heart, pink pepper, black pepper oil, orris, rose, cypriol Heart, vetiver oil | Shipping: Free delivery\nCustomer experience: “This fragrance is beautiful and unique. It’s quite gentle and I find that the opening fades into the mid very quickly on my skin. The opening to me feels almost as if you’re eating a lavender and green tea flavoured desert. I also get a slight hint of pepper shortly after spraying but it isn’t overbearing at all. This fragrance is completely unisex to me but I find this to be a particularly gentlemanly fragrance,” one reviewer writes. Read more reviews here.\nMihan Aromatics\nMikado Bark parfum\nMelbourne-based perfumers Mihan Aromatics have created a scant, clean line of fragrances utilising native ingredients with reserve and grace. This one brings back the scent of the Fitzroy Gardens on long summer evenings.\nSize: 100ml | Key notes: Green pepper, rosemary, basil, dry cinnamon, oud, sandalwood, wet cedar | Shipping: Free delivery\nCustomer experience: “This scent is wonderful! Not too sweet, not too woody, but a nice mix of the two and a bit earthy,” one reviewer writes. Read more reviews here.\nCalvin Klein\nCK One eau de toilette\nNo gender-neutral fragrance list would be complete without the scent that hung in the air throughout the late 1990s. This iconic option by Calvin Klein is clean, youthful and citrus-laden.\nSize: 100ml | Key notes: Green tea, bergamot, cardamon, violet, rose, nutmeg, amber, musk | Shipping: Free delivery over $99\nCustomer experience: “This spray is so beautiful! It's not too overpowering but it has a nice, fresh and clean scent. Perfect for both me and my partner to use,” writes one reviewer. Read more reviews here.\nAesop\nHwyl eau de parfum\nKnown for its earthy, unorthodox formulations, Aesop brings you a smoky, spicy medley of a fragrance in Hwyl—with warm heart notes flecked with vetiver, thyme and moss, this fragrances hints at a unisex floral scent without the sweetness.\nSize: 50ml | Key notes: Thyme, elemi, nutmeg, cypress, geranium, suede, vetiver, cedarwood, patchouli | Shipping: Free delivery\nCustomer experience: “This perfume has been my signature scent for a year now. It's rich and earthy, I love it,” writes one reviewer. Read more reviews here.\nBDK Parfums\nVelvet Tonka eau de parfum\nA fragrance that is sometimes bitter and sometimes sweet as it evolves throughout the wear, inspired by the smells of Morocco and the Atlas Mountains, and a symbol of unisex sensuality with a slight feminine lean, Velvet Tonka by BDK Parfums is a unique, powdery and vintage scent.\nSize: 100ml | Key notes: Orange blossom, almond, rose absolute, tobacco absolute, vanilla absolute, amyris wood essence, amber woods | Shipping: Free delivery\nCustomer experience: “This beautiful perfume is the most gorgeous perfume. It smells utterly sweet and divine. I cannot get enough of it. I get so many compliments when I wear it,” writes one reviewer. Read more reviews here.\nClarins\nEau Dynamisante treatment fragrance\nLeading with sweet and bitter orange, combined with lavandin and eucalyptus and followed by patchouli, Eau Dynamisante by Clarins boasts a fresh, light aroma as well as a stimulating and energising effect on the skin—turning this natural, citrus forward fragrance into a multi-use product.\nSize: 100ml | Key notes: Sweet and bitter orange, mandarin, petitgrain, lavandin, eucalyptus, tarragon, nutmeg, patchouli | Shipping: Free delivery\nCustomer experience: “This is the scent of white linen and a cool breeze,” reads one review. Read more reviews here.\nMalin + Goetz\nDark Rum eau de parfum\nLiquor me up. This dark, sultry fragrance features top notes of bergamot and plum which settle into a leathery, woody base.\nSize: 50ml | Key notes: Rum, leather, plum, bergamot, milk, amber, patchouli | Shipping: Calculated at checkout\nCustomer experience: “This scent is the perfect mixture of feminine and masculine. The Kakadu plum gives such a unique sweetness to the underlying woody/leather scent,” writes one reviewer.\nByredo\nVelvet Haze eau de parfum\nStockholm-based brand Byredo has gained a cult following for the right reasons. Its unisex range is alluring in its minimalism. We’re particular fans of Velvet Haze, but Byredo Bal D'Afrique is also widely beloved for its intriguing and gender-neutral scent.\nSize: 100ml | Key notes: Coconut, hibiscus, bergamot, patchouli, tuberose, osmanthus, musk, cacao, ambrette | Shipping: Free delivery\nCustomer experience: “A faded memory of the 1960s,” reads one review. Read more reviews here.\nPenhaligon’s\nAlUla EDP\nIconic British perfume house Penhaligon’s has been providing stunning fragrances to the world since the late 1860s. If anyone knows the power and craft of a perfect scent, it’s this brand. This ethos culminates in the unisex AlUla eau de parfum, which evokes images of sand and sky in a blend of amber, spices, plums, incense and balmy vanilla notes.\nSize: 100ml | Key notes: Black pepper, Madagascar plum, turmeric root, cardamom oil, vanilla bean, saffron, tobacco accord, patchouli heart, olibanum oil | Shipping: Free delivery\nCustomer experience: “Gorgeous, gorgeous scent. Opens up with a sharp note, cutting through the spiciness, developing on the skin into a mouthwatering, juicy plum. Sweet, juicy and captivating,” writes one reviewer. Read more reviews here.\nThe Body Shop\nFull Ylang Ylang eau de parfum\nIn The Body Shop's Full Flowers range—a new unisex collection where each fragrance is inspired by the whole flower, including all the flower's gendered parts—the Full Ylang Ylang eau de parfum offers a truly unique and delicious spicy, white floral scent extracted from the ylang ylang flowers of Madagascar. Spritz this scent and discover how it evolves throughout the day.\nSize: 75ml | Key notes: Ylang ylang, black pepper, vanilla | Shipping: Free delivery\nCustomer experience: “I’m obsessed, I won’t be getting any other perfume but this for a long time,” writes one reviewer. Read more reviews here.\nLe Labo\nSantal 33 eau de parfum\nWalking outside your door in 2019 meant an almost guaranteed whiff of Santal 33, and it still does today. One of the most loved unisex fragrances around is popular for good reason—notes of sandalwood, papyrus and cardamom keep it earthy and grounded, while iris and violet elevate its pitch to result in an intoxicating, fluid scent.\nSize: 50ml | Key notes: Cardamon, iris, violet, ambrox, Australian sandalwood, papyrus, cedarwood | Shipping: Free over\nCustomer experience: “It's taken me my whole life to find this amazing fragrance. I've always been a fan of more masculine scents like wood smoke, leather, whisky and old leather jackets,” writes one reviewer. Read more reviews here.\nBoy Smells\nGenderful Violet Ends cologne de parfum\nWithin Boy Smells' Genderful universe, a mix of masculine and feminine scent notes are expertly combined to encourage a sense of duality for the wearer. Within this collection, our standout has to be the powerful Violet Ends—with top notes of rhubarb and bergamot and middle notes of black tea and raw tobacco, held in base notes of white birch and smoked papyrus, this perfume is dark, warm and complex.\nSize: 65ml | Key notes: Rhubarb, bergamot, black pepper, black tea, tobacco leaf, incense, white birch, tanned leather, smoked papyrus | Shipping: $43\nCustomer experience: “Feels like a date night smell,” reads one review. Read more reviews here.\nMaison Francis Kurkdjian\nGentle Fluidity Silver Edition eau de parfum\nThis luxury fragrance by Maison Francis Kurkdjian, aptly named Gentle Fluidity, is a multi-faceted scent created from juniper berries, fragrant spices and warm woody notes, held together by sweet and soothing vanilla—a perfect blend.\nSize: 200ml | Key notes: Juniper berries, nutmeg, coriander, musk, ambery woods, vanilla | Shipping: Approximately $57\nCustomer experience: “Even though this is billed as a masculine leaning fragrance, it's most definitely unisex—just not floral or sweet. One of the best perfumes I've experienced (and I have a LOT), it's quite unlike anything I own: clean, cool spices, icily aquatic, refreshing & undeniably elegant. Basically, this smells like money and expensive gin,” writes one reviewer. Read more reviews here.\nDries Van Noten\nSantal Greenery eau de parfum\nFor an outdoorsy, woody scent that delicately balances the contrasting fragrances of sandalwood and green fig leaf, entangled with white musk, light citrus and florals, no one of any gender could go wrong with Dries Van Noten's Santal Greenery.\nSize: 100ml | Key notes: Bergamot, grapefruit, violet leaves, creamy fig, sandalwood, white musk | Shipping: Approximately $57\nCustomer experience: “The most unisex of the lot,” says one reviewer. Read more reviews here.\nAerway\nKnown for offering engineered functional perfumes that can help to influence your mood, emotion and wellbeing, whilst using unisex olfactory designs, Aerway is a new frontier of fragrance. Connect+ uses a blend of sweet, spiced and woody scents to reduce stress and anxiety—as well as help you smell incredible.\nSize: 50ml | Key notes: Thyme, citrus, pink pepper, chestnut, clove, caramel, vanilla, guaic wood, cedarwood | Shipping: Free delivery\nCustomer experience: “I’m pleasantly surprised by the scent… really fresh which is exactly what I like,” writes one reviewer. Read more reviews here.\nMaison Margiela\nWith a blend of orange blossom flowers, clove oil and chestnut atop a comforting vanilla, this fragrance by the french fashion house and parfumerie is warm and transportive.\nSize: 30ml | Key notes: Pink pepper, orange flower, clove oil, chestnut accord, gaïac wood oil, cade oil, vanilla accord, Peru balsam, cashmeran | Shipping: Free delivery\nCustomer experience: “The perfect après ski scent… The olfactory nostalgia of this perfume is *mwah* chef’s kiss. Evocative of sitting by the fire after a day on the slopes, it’s the perfect scent to transport you to where you’d rather be,” writes one reviewer. Read more reviews here.\nWhat is the difference between gender-neutral and gender fluid perfumes?\nAccording to French perfumer Francis Kurkdijian, founder of the eponymous perfume house, everything. Gender neutral scents have been around for a long time, and are designed to be worn and loved by people identifying as any gender due to their blend of notes that have traditionally been divided between perfumes for men and women respectively.\n“But fluidity doesn’t mean genderless. We have to be very specific in our vocabulary,” explains Kurkdjian. “Gender fluidity means one to another, to be able to transition in a fluid manner. This is very very different [to a unisex fragrance].”\nWhat do unisex fragrances smell like?\nUnisex fragrances, by design, encompass a wide spectrum of scents that defy traditional gender categorisations. They are characterised by their versatility and often feature a balanced blend of notes that appeal to a broad audience. Ranging from fresh and citrusy to woody and musky, they often strike a harmonious balance between floral, spicy, and herbal elements.\nUnisex fragrances tend to be less overtly masculine or feminine, making them suitable for anyone who appreciates a scent that transcends conventional boundaries. Ultimately, the beauty of unisex fragrances lies in their ability to adapt to individual preferences and evoke a sense of timeless elegance that appeals to a diverse range of individuals.\nWhere do I buy unisex perfumes?\nUnisex perfumes are becoming more and more common. According to a new products survey done by Mintel, gender-neutral fragrance releases made up 17 per cent of the market in 2010, and by 2018 that figure had ballooned to 51 per cent.\nYou might have grown up spritzing perfumes on at department stores, but now, many of us are shopping online for our scents. Adore Beauty stocks a whole range, including Aesop, Amouage and Who Is Elijah, while make-up stores like Sephora and Mecca have dedicated fragrance sections. For international fragrances that can be hard to source in stores across Australia, major international online retailers like Sense and Selfridges can also be a great option.\nOriginally published as Fluid form: 18 unisex fragrances for universal appeal"}
