{"id": "c9_b_00481", "url": "http://www.china.org.cn/world/Off_the_Wire/2023-11/09/content_116806194.htm", "time": "2023-11-09", "title": "European Investment Bank loans Morocco 500 mln euros", "text": "- 0 Comment(s)Print E-mail Xinhua, November 9, 2023\nRABAT, Nov. 9 (Xinhua) -- The European Investment Bank (EIB) has approved a financing package of 500 million euros (about 535.6 million U.S. dollars) for Morocco's sovereign wealth fund Mohammed VI Fund for Investment.\nThe mandate letter, signed on the sidelines of the Africa Investment Forum opening Wednesday in Marrakech, would support the fund to realize its missions, the Moroccan official news agency MAP reported Thursday.\nThe package was aimed at promoting sustainable investment and reinforcing the kingdom's private sector within the partnership between the European Union and Morocco, according to the report.\nPriority will be given to financing infrastructure projects and deploying innovative financing instruments for Moroccan companies, it said.\nThe EIB announced in October that it will lend Morocco 1 billion euros over the next three years to support its development program.\nThe forum kicked off Wednesday in Marrakech under the theme of \"Unlocking Africa's Value Chains.\" Enditem\nNo comments."}
{"id": "c9_b_00458", "url": "https://economictimes.indiatimes.com/news/earthquake-today", "time": "2026-05-14", "title": "Earthquake Today: Latest Earthquake today news, Videos of Earthquake today - The Economic Times", "text": "Earthquake Today\n'Aliens, nukes, or...': 17 earthquakes shake Area 51 in US in 24 hours, internet goes wild\nA cluster of at least 17 earthquakes, ranging from magnitude 2.5 to 4.4, was recorded near Area 51 within 24 hours. While earthquake swarms are common, the shallow depth of some tremors has raised unusual questions. The proximity to the former Nevada Test Site has fueled speculation about underground activity, though no evidence supports these claims.\nScientists Say Earth’s Inner Core May Have Slowed and Shifted Direction: But It’s Not the Dramatic Change Headlines Suggest\nScientists have found Earth's inner core rotation is not constant. It sometimes spins faster or slower than the outer layers, and can even reverse direction. This internal shift does not impact weather or daily life. However, understanding these core movements helps explain Earth's magnetic field. Research continues to unravel these deep Earth dynamics.\nMagnitude 6.2 earthquake shakes part of northern Japan\nA strong earthquake has rattled northern Japan. The magnitude 6.2 tremor was felt across Hokkaido. Fortunately, no damage or injuries have been reported. Authorities have confirmed no tsunami advisory was issued. This event follows a recent warning about a potential megaquake in the region. Japan remains vigilant following seismic activity.\nMagnitude 6.2 earthquake shakes part of northern Japan\nA strong earthquake has rattled northern Japan. The tremor measured 6.2 magnitude. It struck Hokkaido island early Monday. Fortunately, no damage or injuries have been reported. Authorities did not issue any tsunami warnings. This follows a larger earthquake last week which raised concerns about potential megaquakes.\nUS Highlights News Updates: US airlines spent $1.8 billion more on fuel in March as prices jumped\nUS Highlights News Updates: Major US airlines spent just over $5 billion on jet fuel in March, up 56% and $1.8 billion over February costs, the US Transportation Department said. The cost per gallon of fuel in March was $3.13, up 74 cents, and 31% over February. Fuel use rose 20% in March. Global carriers are contending with surging jet fuel prices since the US-Israeli strikes on Iran disrupted traffic through the Strait of Hormuz, in the air travel industry's worst crisis since the COVID-19 pandemic. Other top stories: US firms add 109,000 jobs, most since early 2025 Private sector job growth in the United States soared past expectations in April, payroll firm ADP said Wednesday, boosted by hiring in health care and a rebound in other sectors. Employment rose by 109,000 jobs, marking the quickest pace of job growth since January 2025, ADP said. This was well above the 84,000 expected by economists surveyed by Dow Jones Newswires and The Wall Street Journal. The numbers come days before the US government releases its jobs data, and is often monitored as a signal for how the broader labor market might be doing -- even if the reports may diverge. India, Vietnam sign 13 MoUs across sectors India and Vietnam signed 13 MoUs spanning sectors such as digital technologies, culture, health regulation, education, tourism, and public sector cooperation during bilateral talks, marking a significant expansion of institutional and strategic ties between the two countries.\nJapan lifts advisory a week after 7.7-magnitude quake\nJapan has lifted a special advisory warning of major earthquakes following a 7.7-magnitude tremor that struck off its northern coast. While the immediate threat has passed, officials caution that the possibility of a major quake remains, as Japan is highly seismically active.\nVijay’s TVK emerges as single largest party in Tamil Nadu shocker; actor-turned-politician leading from both seats\nActor Vijay's new party, Tamilaga Vettri Kazhagam, has caused a major political shift in Tamil Nadu. Early results show TVK as the largest party in the Assembly. This performance disrupts the long-standing hold of the DMK and AIADMK. Vijay's party is now central to government formation discussions. This marks a significant change in the state's political landscape.\nScientists say Earth’s crust is sinking beneath central Turkey in a strange circular pattern, and they believe they finally know why\nScientists have discovered a 'bullseye' of rapid sinking in Turkey's Konya Basin. This unusual land subsidence is linked to deep tectonic activity, where a dense part of Earth's crust is breaking off and sinking. Excessive groundwater use is making the situation worse. This geological event reveals that continents are not static and can change their shape over time.\nTrisha spotted at Vijay’s house on her birthday; Sparks buzz as TVK stuns Tamil Nadu with over 100 seats in debut\nTrisha visits Vijay: On her 43rd birthday, actress Trisha Krishnan visited TVK chief Vijay’s residence in Chennai as early trends showed his party leading in over 100 seats in the Tamil Nadu Assembly elections 2026. The visit has sparked fresh speculation amid Vijay’s ongoing divorce proceedings.\nA construction site buried by Mount Vesuvius may have finally explained why Roman concrete lasted for thousands of years\nAncient Roman concrete's remarkable durability, long attributed to luck, is now understood as a result of a sophisticated \"hot mixing\" process. New research, particularly from Pompeii's preserved ruins, reveals Romans intentionally combined quicklime and ash with water, creating unique chemical reactions. This scientific approach, rather than lost magic, explains their enduring structures and offers vital lessons for modern, sustainable construction.\nHungary's Peter Magyar sworn in as prime minister, ending Viktor Orban's 16-year rule\nHungary inaugurates Peter Magyar as its new prime minister, marking a significant political shift after 16 years of Viktor Orban's rule. Magyar's Tisza party secured a decisive victory, promising to restore democratic institutions, combat corruption, and re-establish strong ties with the European Union.\n\"Geopolitical Earthquake\": UAE quits OPEC to defy Saudi energy dominance, says analysis\nThe UAE has exited OPEC and OPEC+, ending decades of Saudi economic influence. Analysts call it a \"political rebellion\" prioritizing market share and independent foreign policy towards the US, Israel, and Asia. This move aims to monetize oil reserves before they become \"stranded assets\" and fund a green economy transition, potentially reshaping regional energy dynamics and challenging Saudi Arabia's dominance.\nMother’s Day 2026: Why mutual fund SIPs, emergency funds, and insurance are essential for mothers\nFinancial experts emphasize smart planning for mothers' future security, urging early and consistent investing. Flexi-cap and large-cap funds are recommended for growth, while debt and hybrid funds suit retirement. Working mothers can afford higher equity exposure, whereas homemakers benefit from a more conservative approach.\nWhy BJP’s 2026 ‘khela’ is bigger than Mamata Banerjee’s 'Poriborton' that ended over 30 years of Left in Bengal\nWest Bengal witnesses a seismic political shift as the BJP secures a historic victory, ending the Trinamool Congress's long reign. Election trends indicate a decisive mandate for the BJP, signaling a significant 'political reset' in the state. This outcome marks a dramatic turn after decades of TMC dominance, driven by factors including women voters and the Matua community's support.\nThe tiny gas leaks that could help predict earthquakes earlier\nRocks are not silent. They emit chemical signals before breaking. Scientists are learning to understand these signals. This breakthrough allows for better prediction of landslides and earthquakes. New studies link rock structure to gas emissions. This could provide early warnings, saving lives and managing risks. Research continues to refine these methods for real-world application.\nTwin blow: Mamata Banerjee faces big electoral setback, loses bastion Bhabanipur after TMC's crushing defeat\nIn a dramatic turn in West Bengal's Bhabanipur by-election, BJP's Suvendu Adhikari has taken a slender lead over Chief Minister Mamata Banerjee after 16 rounds of counting. The race is incredibly tight, with Adhikari ahead by a mere 563 votes, showcasing a fierce contest in the Chief Minister's stronghold.\nThought of the day by Haruki Murakami: ‘When you come out of the storm, you won’t be the same person who…’ Japanese author’s quote reveals the strength of hidden power during a challenge\nThought of the day: Haruki Murakami has crafted a literary universe where the lines between reality and imagination often blur, yet his insights into human nature remain remarkably clear.\nQuote of the day by Albert Einstein: “He who can no longer pause to wonder and stand rapt in awe is as good as dead; his eyes are...” Battle of Giants: Albert Einstein vs. Niels Bohr — Learn how their historic clash reshaped quantum mechanics, reality, uncertainty, and humanity’s search for truth\nAlbert Einstein quote of the day is gaining fresh attention as millions search for meaning, mental clarity, curiosity, wisdom, and deeper human connection in a fast-moving digital world. Einstein’s powerful quote, “He who can no longer pause to wonder and stand rapt in awe is as good as dead,” reflects a growing global conversation around burnout, emotional numbness, overthinking, and loss of curiosity. The Albert Einstein quote about wonder reminds people that true intelligence begins with awe. Modern life moves fast. Human attention breaks easily. People consume information daily but rarely stop to feel life deeply.\nTamil Nadu Election Winners List 2026: Check the full party-wise candidates winner list\nTamil Nadu Election Winner List 2026: Key trends as TVK