{"id": "c9_b_00483", "url": "https://www.forbes.com/sites/tiffanyleigh/2023/12/29/six-of-the-most-stylish-finds-at-club-med-marrakech-la-palmeraie/", "time": "2023-12-29", "title": "Six Of The Most Stylish Finds At Club Med Marrakech La Palmeraie", "text": "Morocco is a desert dreamscape and in Marrakech - which is the country’s 4th largest city, as well as its major economic and cultural hub - we experience a fortified Medina filled with bustling old-world souks (marketplaces), lush heirloom textiles, cherished trinkets, and intricately made jewelry.\nAnd when you drive 14 minutes north of the Medina, you’ll encounter another oasis: Club Med Marrakech La Palmeraie. The Club Med brand itself was founded in the 1950s by Gérard Blitz. As a leader who pioneered the all-inclusive luxury concept, this was one of the first locations Blitz opened. Today, the property’s style and service here remains unparalleled. In fact, as one of its foundational pillars, Club Med champions the ‘l’Espirit Libre’ Lifestyle. \"When the complexities of everyday life are removed so one can focus on special moments, like having ice cream for breakfast, putting on a ski boots, or dancing with your favorite person, that is what we call luxury – and L’Esprit Libre,” said Kevin Armstrong, Senior Director of Brand & Communications for Club Med North America and the Caribbean. He adds that even as a legacy brand, the company continues to journey forth with simplicity, modernized luxury, and playfulness.\nDespite having over 70 premium resorts around the world that encompass North and South America, Caribbean, Asia, Africa, Europe, and the Mediterranean - each location is as unique and as individual from its sister properties. With that in mind, here are the top style and beauty discoveries at Club Med Marrakech La Palmeraie.\nThe rooms at La Palmeraie; and Le Riad - an Exclusive Collection Space\nThe rooms on the main part of the property on La Palmeraie side feature the hallmarks of Moorish Moroccan interior design thanks to the visionary manifestations of Laurent Maugoust: think geometric tiles on backsplashes and flooring; rich wallpaper, arched doorways, and arabesque motifs which line every room at the hotel.\nTo add to the chic allure of exclusivity, the property also has a ‘hotel nestled within a hotel’. Aptly named Le Riad, these 60 suites designed by Marie Prost are swathed in emerald and golden tones along with offering a private garden/terrace and pool. There’s also an on-site dedicated Le Riad bar and restaurant which offers a premium listing of unique cocktails (highly recommended: the Desert Storm - a blend of Vodka, triple sec, grapefruit juice, lemon, cane sugar) and wines, as well as gourmet creations such as a trio of zaalouk (Cooked Eggplant and Tomato Salad), mechouia (Tunisian-style grilled salad); and local fish en “papillote” finished with lemon butter and julienned vegetables. To gild the lily, at 6pm every evening, guests can indulge in complimentary Castellane champagne.\nBespoke Leather Service and Garments\nMost hotel boutique shops offer an assortment of generic wares for sale. But here, the brand is committed to collaborating with local talents to showcase them as much as possible. In fact, the boutique at Club Med Marrakech offers made-to-measure lambskin clothing services. “The customers can choose from different models within the boutique and their own type of design (everything from dresses, shirts, pants to motorcycle jackets), and the tailor comes to the boutique to take their measurements. Then, they will receive their garment within 48 hours,” the staff explains.\nLocal Artisans at Club Med Marrakech and Secret Fashion Shows:\nTo highlight Morocco's rich artisan heritage, Club Med Marrakech works with local handicrafts to curate and spotlight these talents. Together, they organize a weekly ‘Moroccan Day’ marketplace inviting customers to immerse themselves in local culture at the boutique. Features have previously included ‘Maison De Marrakech’ and ‘Marrakech Mon Amour. The former offers celebratory Takchita garments, kaftans, tunics, jackets; homeware like Berber carpets, and Moroccan leather poufs; and accessories such as basket bags. The latter is a mother founded business which showcases Moroccan craftsmanship such as embroidered baskets, as well as clothing and accessories with a modernist, lively aesthetic (such as branded totes, t-shirts, baseball caps, sweatshirts, and more).\nCinq Mondes - Club Med Spa\nCinq Mondes fuses ancestral knowledge, traditional medicine, and biotechnology together to offer a unique experience that nourishes your body and soul. Here, immersive multi-day spa packages are the way to go. For instance, the property offers energy and balancing rituals; full recovery treatments; and even packaged treatments for kids, couples, and families.\nTop recommendations include their signature Club Med by Cinq Mondes Ayruvedic massage - a hot oil treatment inspired by traditional Abhyanga which aims to release tension and relax muscles; the Stretch Hammam - which includes a purifying exfoliation with Kassa glove (composed of plant-derived cellulose) and traditional Beldi Black Soap (which helps to eliminate impurities, remove dead skin cells, as well as tones/tightens skin); and an adorable My Relax Treatment for littles with features like natural fruit extracts used for a massage and/or moisturizing skincare facial.\nAfterwards, venture to the on-site hammam, a wet steam room that allows for the ultimate in serenity and relaxation.\nTailored Excursions\nIf you want an exclusive take on Marrakech, look no further than to the property’s concierge and excursions desk. With their assistance, you can skip the line at coveted spots like the YSL museum and The Secret Garden, then follow it up with dinner under the starry night sky in the desert. Also, the team can connect you with local guides to help you navigate the souks and find the most unique delicacies - think everything from leather goods, bespoke fashion, beauty products, to local cuisine.\nCuisine\nYou won’t find your usual suspects of resort food, instead - Executive Chef Mohamed Azzabi curates local delicacies to share with guests at his two restaurants - including the famed Moroccan Mechoui: a whole lamb that’s cooked in a pit oven for 2-3 hours with their blend of special spices that include cumin, saffron, and turmeric. “Our two restaurants, The Palmeraie and The El Kebir, offer guests an immersive, culinary experience of Morocco through our internationally influenced menus that feature Moroccan cuisine with locally sourced ingredients and traditional delicacies that are rich in colors, flavors, and scents.”\nAdditionally, Azzabi connects with local initiatives to highlight worthy causes, “we partner with Green Farmers Program, Agrisude NGO, to support local farms found throughout the region to ensure our guests are receiving healthy, fresh, and sustainable products in each dish. Combined with the authentic Moroccan décor and ambiance, our guests enjoy learning about the culture and how our dishes are created to embody true Marrakech cuisine,\" chef explains."}
{"id": "c9_b_00486", "url": "https://www.hurriyetdailynews.com/palestinian-family-doc-applauded-at-marrakech-film-festival-188188", "time": "2023-11-29", "title": "Palestinian family doc applauded at Marrakech Film Festival", "text": "Thirty years ago, Palestinian actor Hiam Abbass left her home to pursue her dreams of being in the movies, joining generations of women in her family who were shaped by exile and “learned to leave everything and start anew.”\nThat's one of the stories told in her director daughter Lina Soualem's documentary “Bye Bye Tiberias,” which received a standing ovation and shouts of “Long Live Palestine” on Nov. 25 at the Marrakech International Film Festival for the film's first screening in the Arab world.\nThe documentary, the Palestinian entry for next year's Academy Award for Best International Feature, follows Abbass and Soualem as the mother-daughter pair laugh, cry and tell the story of four generations of women in their family.\n“Bye Bye Tiberias” first premiered at the Venice International Film Festival, more than a month before the start of the latest Israel-Hamas war, sparked by the militant group's deadly incursion into Israel on Oct. 7.\nIt is the only Palestinian film in competition in Marrakech, where festival organizers have, unlike past years, not held screenings in a popular square that has seen protests against the war.\nIntroducing the documentary on Nov. 25, Soualem and Abbass acknowledged it was an emotional time to present the film, thinking about the children and grandchildren of Palestinian refugees in Gaza.\n“Bye Bye Tiberias” splices together intimate interviews of Soualem's family members, primarily her mother, Abbass, known to both Arab and Western audiences from her work in the television series “ Succession ” and “ Ramy ” as well as films such as “The Lemon Tree” in 2008, the Blade Runner 2049 in 2017, and “Gaza mon amour\" in 2020.\nUnlike other Palestinian narratives, which focus on the broad diaspora, the Gaza Strip or the occupied West Bank, “Bye Bye Tiberias” documents a family displaced by the 1948 Arab-Israeli war from one city to another within modern-day Israel, where they retained citizenship but lived in a Palestinian village largely segregated from Jewish Israeli life.\nRecommended"}
